Preheat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Put a #pot{} of water on to boil with a generous
pinch of @salt{}. Cut the @new potatoes{1}(cut into quarters, no need to peel!) into
quarters. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic
press{} if you have one).

Peel a couple of the outer layers from the @Brussels sprouts{1}, cut off the base,
then cut in half lengthways. Toss your sprouts in a splash of @olive oil{1%splash},
your garlic and a pinch of salt and pepper. Place on a lined #baking tray{} on
the middle shelf of your oven for ~{15-20%mins}.

Boil your potatoes for around ~{10-15%mins}, then drain and leave to the side.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Lightly break up the @black peppercorns{3/4%tsp} using a #pestle and mortar{}.

> You can also put them in a little bag and bash them with a rolling pin or a tin
can!

Roll the @pork medallions{2} in your peppercorns and a good pinch of salt, ensuring
it is completely coated.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%drizzle} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-high
heat. Once the oil is really hot, carefully lay in your pork. Cook for just under
~{2%mins} on each side until you get a nice crisp layer.

> You only need to brown the meat as we'll finish it in your oven.

Once your sprouts are soft, remove them from your oven and place to one side. Place
your pork on another baking tray and put on the middle shelf for ~{10%mins}. At the
same time, fry the @diced chorizo{1} in the now empty #frying pan{} for ~{2%mins}
on medium heat. Toss your sprouts, potatoes and chorizo together in the baking
tray. Cover with #tinfoil{} to keep warm.

> Keep the frying pan for your gravy – no need to wash!

Once your pork is cooked, remove from your oven and rest for a few mins on a
#chopping board{}.

> Resting the pork keeps the meat nice and juicy. The pork is cooked when it is no
longer pink in the middle.

Put the frying pan back on medium heat with the @water{100%ml} and the
@chicken stock pot{1/2}. Bring to the boil and simmer to reduce to a thicker
gravy consistency. Slice your pork into 1cm wide strips. Spoon some of your sprout
and potato mixture onto each plate, lay your pork on top and then spoon over some
gravy.